column8: A fabulous place, no matter what time of year. Best skiing/boarding in the state (no question), and just a beautiful place to spend any amount of time. Hiking, cycling, driving - summer activities are almost as good as the winter ones!

column8: Best steeps in Australia, wonderful views, good snow quality and the highest mountain village in Australia. Very little to offer beginners but a very good offering for intermediates with The Orchard area, excellent experienced offerings with Heavenly Valley and Blue Ribbon and the best expert terrain on offer in Australia with the Extreme Zone

column8: If the earth had a pulse it rose through the mountains, creating their bold silhouette. To my eye, their peaks are the green line of a doctor's graph. I saw those rocks at dawn, those slopes that give home to so much life, a foundation for trees and shrubs, grass and ferns. With blue above and below, in the sky and lake, ever lightening as the sun rose, I knew it would be a good day... I just knew.

column8:
SCAM ALERT!! Where to begin....
Day 1:
Booked accommodation at Bright in hope to do Falls Creek on Saturday and MT Hotham on Sunday based on weather forecast.
Saturday morning road to Falls creek was closed due to tree blocking the road (understandable) so I decided to give Mt Hotham a try.
It took me 5, yes five hours to drive from Bright to Hotham. Left Bright at 8:00am and arrived at Hotham 12:45pm. So what was the problem?
It was not the heavy snow but total disorganization by Hotham staff. At first I thought that there was an accident on the road, with resulting queue all the way to Harrietville.
Instead, staff blocked all the cars at one point requesting to fit chains. There was only 1 Hoy's staff member helping people fitting chains (poor guy), and it was obvious that 95% of drivers
don't know how to fit chains or are afraid to do it by themselves and needed help. The other 2 Mt Hotham staff members on the spot were doing the good old "look busy" thing.
So knowing the weather situation up there, why did you allow all the cars to go up without fitted chains, blocking them all at one point, perfectly aware it would
create chaos? If you don't have enough staff to help people fit the chains you should block all the cars in Harrietville where there is enough space for cars not to block
the road.
12:45pm So when I finally arrived at the village (and paid the resort entry fee) there was no available parking!!! I drove to Dinner Plain and then went back to ask
staff where to park, as there were no spaces available. They told me to drive towards Dinner Plain and just keep driving until I find a free spot (sure mate, there must be spots in Omeo?),
and then catch the bus back to village. If I wanted to go to Dinner Plain why would I buy resort entry? If there is no available parking why do you sell the resort entry and ask
for the licence plate number, threatening with fines if I park in village without resort entry fee? The only option was to drive additional 15-20min towards Dinner Plain,
park the car who knows where, wait 15 min for the bus to arrive, and ride back to the village. So lets say at 1:45pm I would be able to buy a lift pass (if there is no queue),
which would leave me with 2 hours of skiing at best. So icing on the cake, they only have full day price for lift pass, yes, 150$!!!! For what? What a ripoff!!!!
I just drove back to Bright after that.
Day 2:
Having had a bad experience with driving to the resort I decided to take a bus from Bright to the resort. 7:15am Bus was on time, and everything went great until  we arrived in
Harrietville where the bus driver told us that the road is closed due to too much snow on branches over the road. Shortly after, he told us that the trip was canceled because the
road won't be open until 11:30am and there is no point going up there so late (fair enough). He dropped us off in Bright.
Now pardon me but did the resort management experience this now for the first time in history? Were your thinking of maybe trimming the branches over the road just
before the season? No, lets blame it all on mother nature while continuing to charge fees!!!
Conclusion:
So, everything above could have been prevented if someone started thinking a little bit in advance, rather than playing a game of "If I turn my head away form the problem, the problem
will disappear", "It is not how we handle the things it is about how we look" and "Look busy". In total you've cost me 600$ in accommodation and petrol alone, and having to
deal with refund office with resort entry fee and lift pass (pre purchased for the 2nd day).

Now the question is do you expect to have returning customers or do you look for different suckers every year?
column11:
SCAM ALERT!! Where to begin....
Day 1:
Booked accommodation at Bright in hope to do Falls Creek on Saturday and MT Hotham on Sunday based on weather forecast.
Saturday morning road to Falls creek was closed due to tree blocking the road (understandable) so I decided to give Mt Hotham a try.
It took me 5, yes five hours to drive from Bright to Hotham. Left Bright at 8:00am and arrived at Hotham 12:45pm. So what was the problem?
It was not the heavy snow but total disorganization by Hotham staff. At first I thought that there was an accident on the road, with resulting queue all the way to Harrietville.
Instead, staff blocked all the cars at one point requesting to fit chains. There was only 1 Hoy's staff member helping people fitting chains (poor guy), and it was obvious that 95% of drivers
don't know how to fit chains or are afraid to do it by themselves and needed help. The other 2 Mt Hotham staff members on the spot were doing the good old "look busy" thing.
So knowing the weather situation up there, why did you allow all the cars to go up without fitted chains, blocking them all at one point, perfectly aware it would
create chaos? If you don't have enough staff to help people fit the chains you should block all the cars in Harrietville where there is enough space for cars not to block

column8:
This mountain is great. You get onto a run from the parking lot. Good for the keen ones. I learnt on other mountains but here I had a chance to put my skills to the test in a comfortable environment. Started on the lead up tracks to the lifts then went off the sides. Intentionally! As i've been told if you cant see the transition going down its a black run or at least that bit is. Believe! Know your limits. Worth the drive. The entire road is as good as the city roads. No dodgyness!

column8:
Mount Hotham is 5 star for the majestic scenic view, wonderful snow fall experience, and convenient with free bus ride. Food are great and price is just right.
1. Snow lessons and lift prices are just too expensive.
2. Feels unsafe with terrains for beginners-crowded.
3. Not so nice trainer-he showed his frustrations when we can't do what he had demo. First try what does he expect😢
Snow lessons and lifts are rip off-non refundable or transferable and no place for real beginners to practice and be confident to use the lifts.  A tip for beginners or first timers with Zero exp with skiing or snowboarding. 2hrs Beginners lesson will just teach you how to do snowplow and turns. Despite of our effort to learn we were told by the trainer we are not yet ready and cannot use the lift,  (it is mandatory to buy lift pass anyway with lessons, even though they know that beginners can't confidently/ not suitable to use the lift).
2nd day lift pass $191 per head was a waste too since we just felt we are not ready especially the terrain was so busy, and the mountain was too steep, prone to accidents as what we witnessed. The base of the mountain was also crowded full of people doing lessons.
The terrains are for those alreAdy experts pro in skiing or snowboarding.
I hope they can develop a location with mini lifts for real beginners to practice and where pro skiers can't access.
We did really expect that beginners has their own space/place to ski then can hit the slopes once confident. But maybe it's deliberate for patrons to book further with lessons which are really not that so affordable 😅
We did Hire our ski gears and chains with hoys and the staffs are just lovely.

Also it is better to stay in the village rather than  staying in Harrietville or Bright it is risky driving up the hill coz the road is challenging and parking is hard to find, you need to be early 8-9 to get best spots.

Won't go back, maybe falls creek or buller next year. Will try to do research where it is safer for beginners to ski.
This is just our observation. I tried to go speak with the ticket people if there is a chance we can put the lift money into our account for next years visit since we did not really used the lifts coz we are not confident and we don't want ro risk our own safety and others.
But the lady manager was just rude😢

I hope they can develop a location with mini lifts for real beginners to practice and where pro skiers can't access.
We did really expect that beginners has their own space/place to ski then can hit the slopes once confident. But maybe it's deliberate for patrons to book further with lessons which are really not that so affordable 😅
We did Hire our ski gears and chains with hoys and the staffs are just lovely.

Also it is better to stay in the village rather than  staying in Harrietville or Bright it is risky driving up the hill coz the road is challenging and parking is hard to find, you need to be early 8-9 to get best spots.

Won't go back, maybe falls creek or buller next year. Will try to do research where it is safer for beginners to ski.
This is just our observation. I tried to go speak with the ticket people if there is a chance we can put the lift money into our account for next years visit since we did not really used the lifts coz we are not confident and we don't want ro risk our own safety and others.
But the lady manager was just rude😢

column8:
Honestly, besides the increase in cost of lift passes now, I don't know why anyone would ski any other resorts in Oz. Hotham has it all and is superior for steeps and challenging terrain if you want it. Not at long as Thredbo groomers but who cares when you have the steeps and quality.
Great to be back as have been a regular for 15 years now to get my southern hemisphere fix each year.
Certainly a busy year this year based on traffic and numbers but we didn't miss out and got some great snow.
See you next year.
#eddywouldgo

column8:
It’s been like our second home for 25 years. We’ve been to all of the Australian ski resorts and none compare to Hotham. Even New Zealand ski resorts don’t compare. Hotham has real ski in- ski out accommodation, only one T-bar, awesome vertical runs, views to die for, no crowds, the trails on the mountain are linked so well, and the vibe is amazing. Only Japan, the European Alps and Canadian Rockies outdo Hotham, but they are overseas! Yes it’s expensive, but so is else these days. For Australian skiing and snowboarding we wouldn’t go anywhere else but Hotham.

column11: Mt Hotham is in hibernation in mid November. The mountains are nearly void of snow; just a few persistent patches linger. Low cloud in the afternoon approaches from the west, enveloping the peaks in patchy fog. Views are better on the eastern side with impressive vistas to the horizon.

column8: Severally overpriced.  Better value for money in NZ.  Poorly set up lift system and slopes funnelling  down everyone into 1 or 2 runs. Refuses to expand terrain with an even worse resort management board who keep selling off car parks and infrastructure to make $$$.  They are as clueless as the lift company, so don't get me started on them.

column8:
Great Snow; great runs for intermediate and advanced skiers.
That's where the story ends!
We've been skiing at Mt Hotham for many years, but not this year.
Last year's experience of massively overpriced everything, and abysmal service combined with very limited (and sometimes inedible) dinner options has 'burnt us'.
I'll be interested to know whether it's better or worse this year, but given it will cost thousands of dollars to find out, I'll let others find out for me!

column8: Terrible resort. Can’t walk or ski from your lodge to lifts or back. Bus service is totally ineffective. They sell you a lift ticket and then don’t supply the buses to get you around. My kids were left stranded at their lesson end because I waited 90 mins for a bus while my husband walked.

column8: The best place to visit in winters. Mount Hotham wont disappoint you for even a sec of your time you spend there. We had a plan for a day amd ended up extending it to two days just bcz of the activities it offers its visitors. Tobogganing was fun and great activity. Ski for bigginners and for experts both. You can have lessons and so much more. Highly highly recommended place to visit 🤞🤞

column8:
Mount Hotham is an absolute gem in the world of alpine adventures! The ski slopes cater to all levels, the scenic chairlift rides offer breathtaking views, and off-slope activities like snowshoeing are fantastic. The cozy accommodation, friendly staff, and sense of community make it a home away from home. Unforgettable sunrises and sunsets add to the charm. A must-visit destination!

column8:
Four of us visited Mount Hotham on a July weekend to experience what Hotham ski resort has to offer. Three of us opted to learn snowboarding, and one of us opted to learn skiing. At Hotham Central, collecting our ski passes and hiring our snow gear was a seamless process. We all had a lesson in the morning, which were very informative and helpful, and led by some wonderful and charismatic instructors. After our lesson, we all spent the next 2 days enjoying the slopes. I was very impressed with Mount Hotham, including all the friendly staff, the quality of the rental gear, and the ski slopes themselves. What a wonderful place to ski and snowboard. I will definitely be back next year! Thank you!

column11: Worth the drive

column8:
What's there to say about My Hotham that hasn't been said before - the place is iconic for snow lovers and provides you with some of Victoria's most beautiful views

I absolutely love the snow and any opportunity to get involved is a great time for me. This place ticks all the boxes

Coming up here in peak time, there's 2 things you need to consider - there's a lot of people here and it's a costly trip
If you love the snow, none of this will bother you - I didn't care at all

If you're cautious about the snow, I would 100% recommend coming here and experiencing all these amazing views - you'll be converted

column11:
What's there to say about My Hotham that hasn't been said before - the place is iconic for snow lovers and provides you with some of Victoria's most beautiful views

I absolutely love the snow and any opportunity to get involved is a great time for me. This place ticks all the boxes

Coming up here in peak time, there's 2 things you need to consider - there's a lot of people here and it's a costly trip
If you love the snow, none of this will bother you - I didn't care at all

If you're cautious about the snow, I would 100% recommend coming here and experiencing all these amazing views - you'll be converted

column11: Amazing 😻

column8:
"Visiting Mount Hotham in wintertime was an absolute dream come true! From the moment I arrived, I was greeted by the breathtaking beauty of the snow-covered landscape and the inviting atmosphere of the resort.

The skiing and snowboarding opportunities at Mount Hotham are unparalleled. With a variety of slopes suitable for all skill levels, from beginners to seasoned experts, there's something for everyone to enjoy. The well-groomed runs and challenging terrain provided an exhilarating experience that kept me coming back for more day after day.

One of the things that impressed me most about Mount Hotham was the excellent facilities and amenities available. The ski resort offers top-notch equipment rental services, making it easy for visitors to gear up and hit the slopes without any hassle. Additionally, the on-site restaurants and cafes served up delicious meals and warm beverages, perfect for refueling after a day of outdoor adventure.

The staff at Mount Hotham were incredibly friendly, helpful, and knowledgeable. Whether I needed assistance with my equipment or recommendations for the best trails, the staff were always willing to lend a hand and ensure that my experience was nothing short of amazing.

Aside from skiing and snowboarding, Mount Hotham also offers a range of other winter activities to enjoy. From snowshoeing and tobogganing to snowmobiling and scenic chairlift rides, there's no shortage of ways to have fun in the snow.

One of the highlights of my visit was the stunning alpine village atmosphere. The charming accommodations nestled amidst the snow-capped mountains provided the perfect cozy retreat after a day of outdoor adventures.

Overall, my experience at Mount Hotham in wintertime exceeded all expectations. From the thrilling activities to the warm hospitality, it's clear that Mount Hotham is a premier destination for winter enthusiasts. I can't wait to return and create more unforgettable memories in this winter wonderland!"

column11:
"Visiting Mount Hotham in wintertime was an absolute dream come true! From the moment I arrived, I was greeted by the breathtaking beauty of the snow-covered landscape and the inviting atmosphere of the resort.

The skiing and snowboarding opportunities at Mount Hotham are unparalleled. With a variety of slopes suitable for all skill levels, from beginners to seasoned experts, there's something for everyone to enjoy. The well-groomed runs and challenging terrain provided an exhilarating experience that kept me coming back for more day after day.

One of the things that impressed me most about Mount Hotham was the excellent facilities and amenities available. The ski resort offers top-notch equipment rental services, making it easy for visitors to gear up and hit the slopes without any hassle. Additionally, the on-site restaurants and cafes served up delicious meals and warm beverages, perfect for refueling after a day of outdoor adventure.

The staff at Mount Hotham were incredibly friendly, helpful, and knowledgeable. Whether I needed assistance with my equipment or recommendations for the best trails, the staff were always willing to lend a hand and ensure that my experience was nothing short of amazing.

Aside from skiing and snowboarding, Mount Hotham also offers a range of other winter activities to enjoy. From snowshoeing and tobogganing to snowmobiling and scenic chairlift rides, there's no shortage of ways to have fun in the snow.

One of the highlights of my visit was the stunning alpine village atmosphere. The charming accommodations nestled amidst the snow-capped mountains provided the perfect cozy retreat after a day of outdoor adventures.

Overall, my experience at Mount Hotham in wintertime exceeded all expectations. From the thrilling activities to the warm hospitality, it's clear that Mount Hotham is a premier destination for winter enthusiasts. I can't wait to return and create more unforgettable memories in this winter wonderland!"

Amazing views of the snowy mountains and the whole area looks flattering!!
There’s a bunch of snow activities happening during the season.
The hardest part was parking. It’s almost impossible to find a good parking spot if you’re not very early! You’ll have to park somewhere else and take the bus to the location where activities take place :(
And the free buses would be almost packed with people, and you’ll hardly find some breathing space!😕
Also, make sure you guys bring the skiing equipments because the gear charges at Mt Hotham is double the amount you pay elsewhere!!!

column8: Guest attended manager is so arrogant. She is an Asian lady she has no sense how to talk to clients. They’re just ripping your pockets. We were a group of 4, on 29th July 2024 each person paid more than $200 so we can experience the view of lift chair but they wouldn’t allow us to sit on it. They give you the half information at the time of purchasing the tickets than later on they won’t stick on what they said before. They didn’t even refunded the money she said you use the service already. How the hell we used the service when they didn’t let us do what we paid for. At end she offers $25 refund like seriously man I paid $250 and in return you just offering $25 back. They’re a big scammer. The all they care about is money. Then they charge me $64 twice for permit just for few hours parking and they not even returning that money either.

column8:
We found Hotham not at all set up for beginners. Our basic lesson was as basic as you get - How to attach the skis and how to snow plough, then we were set loose. There were no slopes on Hotham that we felt suitable for a beginner. The "carpet" was an absolute joke, a sheer drop with no space to turn and all of the beginners in this area just fell down before they hit the barriers and likely hurt themselves. We asked some of the instructors for advice on which slopes were better for beginners and were sent to Big D carpet. When we got there we were told the only way to get to the carpet was to walk up the slopes...after a painstaking 30 minute climb we were told we couldn't be there as they had too many children then today and sent back down. As we ski'd back down the mountain - badly - An instructor pulled up with a group of children and instructed the children that we were "gerrys" and that we didn't belong on the slope!

In summary, the experience was not one that we would go out of our way to repeat and that their own instructor made comments to a group of young children about how we didn’t belong there was appalling.

column8:
Mount Hotham is a mountain located in the Victorian Alps of the Great Dividing Range, in the Australian state of Victoria. The mountain is located approximately 357 kilometres (222 mi) north east of Melbourne, 746 kilometres (464 mi) from Sydney, and 997 kilometres (620 mi) from Adelaide by road. The nearest major road to the mountain is the Great Alpine Road. The mountain is named after Charles Hotham, Governor of Victoria from 1854 to 1855. Mount Hotham's summit rises to an altitude of 1,862 metres (6,109 ft) AHD.
Mount Hotham Alpine Resort, a commercial alpine resort, is located on the slopes of Mount Hotham summit and nearby mountains.
Administratively, the mountain is within Mount Hotham Alpine Resort unincorporated area, land which is managed by Alpine Resorts Victoria. This unincorporated area is surrounded by Alpine Shire

Mount Hotham's summit rises to an altitude of 1,862 metres (6,109 ft) AHD.
Mount Hotham Alpine Resort, a commercial alpine resort, is located on the slopes of Mount Hotham summit and nearby mountains.

It’s such an amazing journey riding on the higher parts of the great Alpine Road towards Mount Hotham Summit in Summer! It’s quiet without the skiing pack in winter and despite the strong wind, the temperature now is like paradise on 1800metre altitude. Deciding to do some hikes on the ridges later because of its stunning ranges the nature here offers! This place reminds me of Tibet, China when the car goes through the winding, ridges like a wind piercer; The skiing paradise also resonates Whakapapa in New Zealand but at a much larger scale for sure and more friendly for expert skiers not the beginners - around 70% black path  lanes!

column8:
For someone who has seen and experi3nce snow for the first time, I would say that this place is majestic. It's an enormous place as it offers different kinds of activities and levels in different areas of the mountain. There are also free shuttles to visit different parts of the place.
Activities offered are toboggan sledding, snowboarding and skiing.
Toboggan sledding is favourable for first timers but if you want a challenge, snowboarding can be the next option.
The downside is, you have to carry your equipment everytime unless you decide to bring it back to the rental shop.
Also, staff in rental shops are moody as they can be impatient with customers and food is also expenaive and not in good quality. So if you have your own suits and equipment, also food, better to bring them but if it can be a hassle or only using it for once then better rent or borrow from friends or family who have snow gears and equipment.
Overall, the place was magnificent and it is a must place to visit during winter even if only for once.
The travel time from the CBD by a private car can take up to four and a half hours. Tour operators are also available but getting in contact with them in advance is a must.

column8:
I had a very frustrating experience at Mount Hotham. I paid for a Resort Entry Pass, but when I arrived, I was told that snow chains couldn’t be fitted to my car. I had no choice but to take a round-trip taxi, which, along with day passes, ended up costing me $445.50 out of pocket.

It was incredibly disappointing to spend that much just to reach the resort, especially when this issue could have been avoided with better information beforehand.

I strongly recommend that Mount Hotham improve their booking system by adding a vehicle registration check to verify tyre sizes and snow chain compatibility. Or at the very least, show a clear warning during booking that lists tyre sizes incompatible with snow chains.

This way, people can arrange a different car for the trip, save money, and actually enjoy their time at the resort.

column8:
Mount Hotham is a mountain located in the Victorian Alps of the Great Dividing Range, in the Australian state of Victoria. The mountain is located approximately 357 kilometres (222 mi) north east of Melbourne, 746 kilometres (464 mi) from Sydney, and 997 kilometres (620 mi) from Adelaide by road. The nearest major road to the mountain is the Great Alpine Road. The mountain is named after Charles Hotham, Governor of Victoria from 1854 to Mount Hotham Alpine Resort, a commercial alpine resort, is located on the slopes of Mount Hotham summit and nearby mountains.

Administratively, the mountain is within Mount Hotham Alpine Resort unincorporated area, land which is managed by Alpine Resorts Victoria. This unincorporated area is surrounded by Alpine

Visitors need to purchase an entry permit to enter the resort during winter. The resort entry fee contributes to essential services for guests around the mountain, including ski patrol, the free village buses, snow clearing of car parks in the village, waste management and environmental initiatives.

Best time to visit is from mid June to July end.

column11:
Mount Hotham is a mountain located in the Victorian Alps of the Great Dividing Range, in the Australian state of Victoria. The mountain is located approximately 357 kilometres (222 mi) north east of Melbourne, 746 kilometres (464 mi) from Sydney, and 997 kilometres (620 mi) from Adelaide by road. The nearest major road to the mountain is the Great Alpine Road. The mountain is named after Charles Hotham, Governor of Victoria from 1854 to Mount Hotham Alpine Resort, a commercial alpine resort, is located on the slopes of Mount Hotham summit and nearby mountains.

Administratively, the mountain is within Mount Hotham Alpine Resort unincorporated area, land which is managed by Alpine Resorts Victoria. This unincorporated area is surrounded by Alpine

Visitors need to purchase an entry permit to enter the resort during winter. The resort entry fee contributes to essential services for guests around the mountain, including ski patrol, the free village buses, snow clearing of car parks in the village, waste management and environmental initiatives.

Best time to visit is from mid June to July end.

column8:
We visited Mt Hotham yesterday and had an amazing time! The day pass for the car was $67, which gave us access to the whole area. Upon arrival around 9 AM, we were greeted by fresh snowfall—it was snowing heavily throughout the day, making it a perfect winter wonderland.

Chains were compulsory on all vehicles, and we rented one along with some snow play equipment. The tobogganing was an absolute highlight—super fun and perfect for all ages!

What really impressed us was the convenience of the free shuttle buses running throughout Hotham Village, which made getting around easy even in the snow. The entire experience was smooth, safe, and well-organised.

Highly recommend Mt Hotham for a snowy adventure—whether you’re skiing, tobogganing, or just playing in the snow, there’s something for everyone!

column11:
We visited Mt Hotham yesterday and had an amazing time! The day pass for the car was $67, which gave us access to the whole area. Upon arrival around 9 AM, we were greeted by fresh snowfall—it was snowing heavily throughout the day, making it a perfect winter wonderland.

Chains were compulsory on all vehicles, and we rented one along with some snow play equipment. The tobogganing was an absolute highlight—super fun and perfect for all ages!

What really impressed us was the convenience of the free shuttle buses running throughout Hotham Village, which made getting around easy even in the snow. The entire experience was smooth, safe, and well-organised.

Highly recommend Mt Hotham for a snowy adventure—whether you’re skiing, tobogganing, or just playing in the snow, there’s something for everyone!

column8:
I rolled into Hotham mid-winter, skis strapped, ready for adventure. The village nestled amid snow-dusted peaks felt magical. After warming up on gentle runs, I tackled steeper gullies like Mary’s Slide—what a rush! Nights were spent sipping hot chocolate in the lodge, swapping slope stories by the fire. I snagged early “First Tracks” on Heavenly Valley—pure bliss under the pink dawn light.

Returning in spring, I zipped into a Hypedome pod, helmed a glamping fondue dinner, and wandered wildflower trails in silence. Star-filled nights and snowgum breezes made it all unforgettable.

Highly recommend an overnight trip if you want a peaceful and magical snow experience!

column8: Do not use this mountain unless there is no alternative. The price you pay for what you get makes this a low value option. I spent 4 days of which I was able to ski 3 because the operator closed the lifts. The reimbursement was less than half what I paid for the day. Essentially, any excuse to take money from you is exploited. Having done an estimate of a trip to Japan, it is reasonably comparable and Queenstown more so when including entry fees, food, hire and parking versus snow coverage.

Having done an estimate of a trip to Japan, it is reasonably comparable and Queenstown more so when including entry fees, food, hire and parking versus snow coverage.

column8:
I rented skates with my friends and an instructor. Afterwards, we were late because the car had issues. The staff recommended a refund and rebooking, and said the refund would be made to the original payment card. At first, I felt strange that I was asked to pay an additional 300+ baht for the new booking. Now, it’s been almost two weeks — I’ve called and emailed, but the staff have been very unhelpful. They said they would handle it, but nothing has been done.

I feel like I’ve been scammed. If anyone else has experienced a situation like this, I wouldn’t trust the staff here. Please resolve this matter urgently and refund my money. Thank you very much.

Mt Hotham is one of the best ski destinations in Australia! The snow was perfect, and the slopes are great for all skill levels. The staff were super helpful and friendly, making the whole experience smooth and enjoyable.

Parking was easier than expected, and the drive up was beautiful — stunning views all the way. There are plenty of great lookouts to stop and enjoy the scenery.

The village has a great vibe, with nice food and everything you need for a comfortable stay. Highly recommend Mt Hotham for anyone looking for a fun and memorable snow trip!
